    border: 1px solid #ddd;
    padding: 10px;
    margin: 10px 0;
    border-radius: 5px;
    line-height: 1.6;"><p>To plot the age category for male or female with the year they died, and the year of death among different taxons in R, you can use various plotting libraries such as ggplot2 or base R graphics.</p>
<p>Here's an example using the ggplot2 library:</p>
<pre><code class="language-R"># Assuming you have a data frame called 'data' with columns: 'age_category', 'year_of_death', 'gender', 'taxon'

library(ggplot2)

# Plotting age category for male and female with the year of death
ggplot(data, aes(x = year_of_death, fill = age_category)) +
  geom_bar(data = subset(data, gender == &quot;Male&quot;), position = &quot;stack&quot;) +
  geom_bar(data = subset(data, gender == &quot;Female&quot;), position = &quot;stack&quot;) +
  labs(x = &quot;Year of Death&quot;, y = &quot;Count&quot;, fill = &quot;Age Category&quot;)

# Plotting age category for male and female with the year of death grouped by taxon
ggplot(data, aes(x = year_of_death, fill = age_category)) +
  geom_bar(data = subset(data, gender == &quot;Male&quot;), position = &quot;stack&quot;) +
  geom_bar(data = subset(data, gender == &quot;Female&quot;), position = &quot;stack&quot;) +
  facet_wrap(~ taxon) +
  labs(x = &quot;Year of Death&quot;, y = &quot;Count&quot;, fill = &quot;Age Category&quot;)
</code></pre>
<p>Note that you need to replace 'data' with the actual name of your data frame, and 'age_category', 'year_of_death', 'gender', and 'taxon' with the actual column names from your data frame. Additionally, you may need to customize the plot further to match your specific data and requirements.</p></div>

