    border-radius: 5px;
    line-height: 1.6;"><p>To create a machine learning module that predicts the game's next random color based on past game data, you could utilize simple statistics and probability.</p>
<p>Here is a simple implementation that predicts the next color and calculates the accuracy of each color based on occurrences:</p>
<pre><code class="language-python">import json
import random

# Load past game data
past_games = json.loads('[&quot;red&quot;, &quot;red&quot;, &quot;purple&quot;, &quot;purple&quot;, &quot;purple&quot;, &quot;red&quot;, &quot;red&quot;, &quot;red&quot;, &quot;purple&quot;, &quot;red&quot;, &quot;yellow&quot;, &quot;red&quot;, &quot;purple&quot;, &quot;red&quot;, &quot;purple&quot;, &quot;purple&quot;, &quot;yellow&quot;, &quot;red&quot;, &quot;purple&quot;, &quot;purple&quot;, &quot;yellow&quot;, &quot;red&quot;, &quot;yellow&quot;, &quot;red&quot;, &quot;red&quot;, &quot;purple&quot;, &quot;red&quot;, &quot;red&quot;, &quot;red&quot;, &quot;purple&quot;, &quot;purple&quot;, &quot;red&quot;, &quot;purple&quot;, &quot;purple&quot;]')

# Count occurrences of each color
color_counts = {&quot;yellow&quot;: 0, &quot;red&quot;: 0, &quot;purple&quot;: 0}
for color in past_games:
    color_counts[color] += 1

# Calculate probability for each color
